<Docs
  title="Introduction"
  eyebrow="Documentation"
  summary="ubuntu_setup is a single repository that turns a fresh Ubuntu 26.04 install into a workstation that's beautiful, keyboard-driven, private, and hardened — in one command."
>
  <p>
    Most dotfiles projects ask you to trust a wall of shell you can't read, or
    to learn a configuration framework before you can change a single alias.
    <strong>ubuntu_setup</strong> takes the opposite position: everything is a
    plain file, laid out where you'd expect it, and the whole thing installs
    with one script you can read top to bottom.
  </p>
  <p>
    It's built for technical users — people who live in a terminal, run their
    own machines, and would rather own their configuration than inherit
    someone else's magic. Out of the box it disables Ubuntu's phone-home
    telemetry, brings up a firewall, and tunes the machine for battery. If
    that's the machine you want, this is a baseline worth starting from.
  </p>

  <h2 id="the-one-command">The one command</h2>
  <p>
    On a clean Ubuntu 26.04 machine, this is the entire installation:
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose my-6">
    <CopyCommand command="git clone https://github.com/etmartinkazoo/ubuntu_setup.git && cd ubuntu_setup && ./setup/bootstrap.sh" />
  </div>
  <p>
    The bootstrap is <strong>idempotent</strong> — running it again is safe and
    only fills in what's missing. It never overwrites your files without first
    backing them up.
  </p>

  <h2 id="commitments">The six commitments</h2>
  <p>These are principles, not a feature list. Every default in the repo traces back to one of them:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Beautiful.</strong> A workspace worth looking at — considered type, colour, and defaults.</li>
    <li><strong>Keyboard-driven.</strong> Panes, navigation, and the commands you run all day are a keystroke away.</li>
    <li><strong>Private.</strong> Telemetry, crash reporting, and phone-home pings are off from the first run.</li>
    <li><strong>Hardened.</strong> A default-deny firewall, automatic security updates, and kernel hardening.</li>
    <li><strong>Efficient.</strong> Fast tools and real power management for all-day battery.</li>
    <li><strong>Focused.</strong> The browser and DNS block the noise, with a distraction list you control.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="principles">How it's built</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Plain files over abstractions.</strong> No DSL, no framework. If you know bash, you already know how this works.</li>
    <li><strong>One repository.</strong> Your shell, multiplexer, packages, and system policy all live and version together.</li>
    <li><strong>Idempotent and reversible.</strong> Run it as many times as you like. Every replaced file is backed up first.</li>
    <li><strong>A baseline, not a cage.</strong> It's meant to be forked and edited — not adopted wholesale and left untouched.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who it's for</h2>
  <p>
    It assumes you're comfortable on the command line and want opinionated
    defaults to build on, not a beginner-friendly GUI installer. It's built
    around <strong>Framework 13 and 16 laptops</strong>, but the
    hardware-specific steps are guarded behind a check — run it on any x86_64
    Ubuntu machine and those steps simply skip while everything else installs
    the same.
  </p>

